A tool that fetches search results forwards the AbortSignal to fetch, so the network request is automatically cancelled if the agent aborts the operation mid-flight.

```js
execute: async (input, client) => {
  const res = await fetch(\`/api/search?q=\${input.query}\`, { signal: client.signal });
  return { content: [{ text: await res.text() }] };
}
```

Adapt server response based on who submitted the form:

```javascript
form.addEventListener('submit', (event) => {
  if (event.agentInvoked) {
    // Return JSON for the agent
    respondWith({ results: data });
  } else {
    // Render full HTML for the human
    renderResultsPage(data);
  }
});
```

During a logout flow, the app calls clearContext() before redirecting to the sign-in page, ensuring no authenticated tools like "view-orders" or "manage-payment" remain available to agents even momentarily.

```js
// Wipe all tools and context in a single call
navigator.modelContext.clearContext();
// Agents now see zero tools until the next registration
```

A tool returns both a text summary and a chart image in a single content array, giving the agent multiple pieces of information to work with:

```js
execute: async (input) => ({
  content: [
    { type: "text", text: `Found 3 results for "${input.query}".` },
    { type: "image", data: chartBase64, mimeType: "image/png" }
  ]
})
```

A site progressively enhances with WebMCP tools when available, falling back to a standard interface otherwise:

```js
if ("modelContext" in navigator) {
  navigator.modelContext.provideContext({ tools: myTools });
  console.log("WebMCP tools registered — agents can discover this site.");
} else {
  console.log("WebMCP not supported in this browser — using standard UI.");
}
```

```javascript
await navigator.modelContext.registerTool({
  name: 'search-products',
  description: 'Search the product catalog',
  inputSchema: { type: 'object', properties: { query: { type: 'string' } } },
  execute: async ({ query }) => [{ text: await searchAPI(query) }]
});
```
This registers a product search tool that agents can call by providing a query string.

A flight search tool declares a detailed inputSchema with type constraints and pattern validation:

```js
inputSchema: {
  type: "object",
  properties: {
    origin: { type: "string", description: "Departure IATA airport code", pattern: "^[A-Z]{3}$" },
    destination: { type: "string", description: "Arrival IATA airport code", pattern: "^[A-Z]{3}$" },
    date: { type: "string", format: "date", description: "Travel date in YYYY-MM-DD format" }
  },
  required: ["origin", "destination", "date"]
}
```

A banking tool uses the client to require explicit user confirmation before executing a money transfer:

```js
execute: async (input, client) => {
  const ok = await client.requestUserInteraction(
    () => confirm(`Transfer $${input.amount} to ${input.recipient}?`)
  );
  if (!ok) return { content: [{ type: "text", text: "Transfer cancelled by user." }] };
  return { content: [{ type: "text", text: doTransfer(input) }] };
}
```

Register two tools at once using provideContext(), then later remove one dynamically when the user navigates away from the store section of the application to keep the tool set current:

```js
const ctx = navigator.modelContext;
ctx.provideContext({ tools: [searchTool, addToCartTool] });
// User leaves the store section
ctx.unregisterTool("add-to-cart");
// Only searchTool remains available to agents
```

A recipe site registers its full tool set at startup using a single provideContext call with a ModelContextOptions dictionary:

```js
navigator.modelContext.provideContext({
  tools: [
    { name: "search-recipes", description: "Find recipes by ingredient", inputSchema: searchSchema, execute: searchFn },
    { name: "save-recipe", description: "Bookmark a recipe for later", inputSchema: saveSchema, execute: saveFn }
  ]
});
```

A to-do app checks for WebMCP support on page load and registers a tool if available:

```js
if ("modelContext" in navigator) {
  navigator.modelContext.registerTool({
    name: "add-todo",
    description: "Add an item to the to-do list",
    inputSchema: { type: "object", properties: { text: { type: "string" } }, required: ["text"] },
    execute: async (input) => { addItem(input.text); return { content: [{ type: "text", text: "Done" }] }; }
  });
}
```

```javascript
// Install: npm install @mcp-b/global
import '@mcp-b/global';

// Now works on ANY browser, native or polyfilled
await navigator.modelContext.registerTool({
  name: 'get-weather',
  description: 'Get current weather',
  execute: async ({ city }) => [{ text: `Weather in ${city}: Sunny, 72°F` }]
});
```

A flight-booking SPA calls provideContext() on each route change. On the search page it exposes a "search-flights" tool; on the results page it swaps in "select-seat" and "add-baggage"; at checkout it offers "confirm-booking". One call per transition, always in sync.

```js
navigator.modelContext.provideContext({
  tools: [{ name: "add-item", description: "Add item to cart", inputSchema: { type: "object" }, execute: async (input) => ({ content: [{ text: "Done" }] }) }]
});
```

A React todo app uses react-webmcp to register an `add-todo` tool inside a component:
```jsx
const {} = useWebMCPTool({
  name: 'add-todo',
  description: 'Add a new todo item to the list',
  execute: ({ text }) => addTodo(text)
});
```
When the TodoList component mounts, agents can add todos. When the user navigates away from the page, the tool automatically deregisters — keeping the tool surface area in sync with the UI.

A chat application registers a "translate-message" tool only after the user enables the translation plugin in settings, without affecting the already-registered "send-message" and "search-history" tools.

```js
navigator.modelContext.registerTool({
  name: "search",
  description: "Search items in the catalog",
  inputSchema: { type: "object", properties: { query: { type: "string" } } },
  execute: async (input, client) => ({ content: [{ text: "Results for: " + input.query }] })
});
```

A tool that places an order calls requestUserInteraction() to show a confirmation dialog with the order total before charging the user's credit card. If the user declines, the tool returns a cancellation.

```js
const confirmed = await client.requestUserInteraction(() => confirm("Buy this item for $29.99?"));
if (!confirmed) return { content: [{ text: "Purchase cancelled by user." }] };
```

A page uses a single event listener to handle all incoming tool calls, routing them by tool name and responding with structured content that the agent can interpret and relay to the user.

```js
window.agent.addEventListener('toolcall', (event) => {
  if (event.toolName === 'get-price') {
    event.respondWith(Promise.resolve({ content: [{ text: "$19.99" }] }));
  }
});
```

Using a React SDK abstraction:
```jsx
function TodoApp() {
  useTool('add-todo', 'Add a to-do item', { title: 'string' },
    async ({ title }) => { addTodo(title); return [{ text: 'Added!' }]; }
  );
  return <TodoList />;
}
```
The hook handles registration on mount, cleanup on unmount, and schema generation from the parameter types.

An e-commerce tool set uses annotations to distinguish safe browsing from risky mutations:

```js
{ name: "view-cart", annotations: { readOnlyHint: true }, /* ... */ }
{ name: "place-order", annotations: { readOnlyHint: false }, /* ... */ }
```
The agent freely calls view-cart for information gathering but requests explicit user confirmation before invoking place-order.

A weather tool's execute callback fetches data from an API and returns structured content the agent can relay to the user.

```js
// WebIDL: callback ToolExecuteCallback = Promise<any> (object input, ModelContextClient client);
execute: async (input, client) => {
  const data = await fetch(`/api/weather?city=${input.city}`);
  const result = await data.json();
  return { content: [{ text: `${result.temp}°F in ${input.city}` }] };
}
```

Style a form to show when an agent is interacting with it:

```css
form:tool-form-active {
  border: 2px solid #3b82f6;
  opacity: 0.8;
  position: relative;
}
form:tool-form-active::after {
  content: "🤖 AI is filling this form";
  position: absolute; top: -1.5em;
}
```

Provide visual feedback during agent submission:

```css
form:tool-submit-active {
  pointer-events: none;
  opacity: 0.5;
}
form:tool-submit-active button[type="submit"] {
  background: #f59e0b;
}
form:tool-submit-active button[type="submit"]::after {
  content: " ⏳";
}
```

A security middleware listens for toolactivated events and blocks any tool call that requires authentication when the user session is not active, returning a helpful message instead.

```js
window.addEventListener('toolactivated', (event) => {
  if (requiresAuth(event.toolName) && !isUserLoggedIn()) {
    event.preventDefault();
    event.respondWith({ content: [{ text: "Please log in first." }] });
  }
});
```

A tool that opens a confirmation modal listens for toolcancel to dismiss the dialog if the agent cancels before the user responds, keeping the UI clean, preventing user confusion, and freeing resources.

```js
window.addEventListener('toolcancel', (event) => {
  if (event.toolName === 'confirm-purchase') {
    dismissModal('purchase-confirmation');
    console.log('Purchase tool cancelled by agent.');
  }
});
```

An e-commerce site unregisters the "apply-employee-discount" tool when it detects the employee session has expired, preventing agents from attempting a discount that would fail server-side. The remaining tools stay active.

```js
// Remove a single tool by name
navigator.modelContext.unregisterTool("add-item");
// The tool is now invisible to agents — no further calls can reach it
```

definition:
When an architect designs a building, they don't just sketch ideas on a napkin — they produce formal blueprints with precise measurements that any construction team can follow. WebIDL is the blueprint language for web APIs.

Web Interface Definition Language (WebIDL) is a formal specification language maintained by the WHATWG (Web Hypertext Application Technology Working Group). Every browser API you've ever used — `fetch()`, `querySelector()`, `addEventListener()` — is formally defined in WebIDL before any browser implements it. WebIDL describes the exact shape of interfaces: what methods they have, what parameters those methods accept, what types are returned, and under what conditions errors are thrown.

WebMCP's API surface is entirely defined in WebIDL. The `ModelContext` interface, the `ModelContextTool` dictionary, the `ToolExecuteCallback` type, the `ModelContextClient` interface — all are specified in WebIDL blocks within the Bikeshed source file. For example:

```
[Exposed=Window, SecureContext]
interface ModelContext {
  undefined provideContext(ModelContextOptions options);
};
```

This tiny block encodes several critical decisions. `Exposed=Window` means the API is available in main window contexts (not in workers — at least not yet). `SecureContext` means it requires HTTPS — no insecure HTTP pages can use WebMCP. The `undefined` return type means `provideContext()` doesn't return a value. The `ModelContextOptions` parameter type links to another definition elsewhere in the spec.

WebIDL matters because it eliminates ambiguity. When a spec says a method 'accepts a string,' WebIDL specifies whether that's a `DOMString` (UTF-16), `USVString` (scalar values only), or `ByteString` (Latin-1). When a spec says a parameter is 'optional,' WebIDL specifies its default value. Browser engineers implementing WebMCP in Chrome, Firefox, or Safari all read the same WebIDL and produce compatible implementations.

The Bikeshed tool validates WebIDL blocks at build time, catching syntax errors and type mismatches before they enter the published spec. This is why WebMCP's API contracts are reliable — they're machine-validated, not just human-reviewed.
